"Delille D., Pelletier E., Rodriguez-Blanco A., Ghiglione J.-F.","Effects of nutrient and temperature on degradation of petroleum hydrocarbons in sub-Antarctic coastal seawater",2009,"Polar Biology","32","10",,"1521","1528",,,10.1007/s00300-009-0652-z,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-76149116175&partnerID=40&md5=fe58538325b4aa0eb9c8e979e8fb0709","Laboratoire ARAGO, UPMC Univ Paris 06, UMR 7621, Avenue Fontaulé, BP 44, 66650 Banyuls-sur-Mer, France; Laboratoire d'Océanographie Biologique de Banyuls, CNRS, UMR7621, Avenue Fontaulé, BP 44, 66650 Banyuls-sur-Mer, France; Institut des Sciences de la Mer de Rimouski (ISMER), Université du Québec à Rimouski, 310 allée des Ursulines, Rimouski G5L 3A1, Canada","Delille, D., Laboratoire ARAGO, UPMC Univ Paris 06, UMR 7621, Avenue Fontaulé, BP 44, 66650 Banyuls-sur-Mer, France, Laboratoire d'Océanographie Biologique de Banyuls, CNRS, UMR7621, Avenue Fontaulé, BP 44, 66650 Banyuls-sur-Mer, France; Pelletier, E., Institut des Sciences de la Mer de Rimouski (ISMER), Université du Québec à Rimouski, 310 allée des Ursulines, Rimouski G5L 3A1, Canada; Rodriguez-Blanco, A., Laboratoire ARAGO, UPMC Univ Paris 06, UMR 7621, Avenue Fontaulé, BP 44, 66650 Banyuls-sur-Mer, France, Laboratoire d'Océanographie Biologique de Banyuls, CNRS, UMR7621, Avenue Fontaulé, BP 44, 66650 Banyuls-sur-Mer, France; Ghiglione, J.-F., Laboratoire ARAGO, UPMC Univ Paris 06, UMR 7621, Avenue Fontaulé, BP 44, 66650 Banyuls-sur-Mer, France, Laboratoire d'Océanographie Biologique de Banyuls, CNRS, UMR7621, Avenue Fontaulé, BP 44, 66650 Banyuls-sur-Mer, France","In an attempt to evaluate the potential of petroleum bioremediation at high latitudes environments, microcosm studies using Antarctic coastal seawater contaminated with diesel or crude oil were conducted in Kerguelen Archipelago (49°22′S, 70°12′E). Microcosms were incubated at three different temperatures (4, 10 and 20°C). During experiments, changes observed in microbial assemblages (total direct count, heterotrophic cultivable microorganisms and hydrocarbon-degrading microorganisms) were generally similar for all incubation temperatures, but chemical data showed only some slight changes in biodegradation indices [Σ(C12-C20)/Σ(C21-C32) and C17/pristane]. The complete data set provided strong evidence of the presence of indigenous hydrocarbon-degrading bacteria in Antarctic seawater and their high potential for hydrocarbon bioremediation. The rate of oil degradation could be increased by the addition of a commercial fertilizer, but water temperature had little effects on biodegradation efficiency which is in conflict with the typical temperature-related assumption predicting 50% rate reduction when temperature is reduced by 10°C. Global warming of Antarctic seawater should not increase significantly the rate of oil biodegradation in these remote regions. © Springer-Verlag 2009.","Antarctic seawater; Bioremediation agents; Crude oil; Diesel oil; Temperature","biodegradation; bioremediation; coastal water; community dynamics; fertilizer; latitude; marine pollution; microbial activity; microcosm; nutrient; petroleum hydrocarbon; subantarctic region; temperature effect; French Southern Territories; Kerguelen Islands; Bacteria (microorganisms)",,,,,,"Aislabie, J., Hydrocarbon-degrading bacteria in oil-contaminated soils near Scott Base, Antarctica (1997) Ecosystem Processes in Antarctica's Ice-Free Landscape, pp. 253-258. , W. B. Lyons, C. Howard-Williams, and I. Hawes (Eds.), Rotterdam: Balkema Publishers Ltd; Aislabie, J., Foght, J., Hydrocarbon-degrading bacteria in contaminated soils (2008) Bioremediation of Petroleum Hydrocarbons in Cold Regions, pp. 69-83. , D. F. Filler, I. Snape, and D. L. Barns (Eds.), Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; Aislabie, J., McLeod, M., Fraser, R., Potential for biodegradation of hydrocarbons in soil from the Ross dependency, Antarctica (1998) Appl Microbiol Biotechnol, 49, pp. 210-214; Aislabie, J., Fraser, R., 